    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 20th with a clear top-tier anchor in **Yordan Alvarez** (78.41), whose favorable matchup against Cecconi and an elite xwOBA of 0.393 make him the day\u2019s most bankable producer. While **Yordan Alvarez** provides the raw power, **Trea Turner** (69.16) and **Kyle Schwarber** (68.80) offer the highest combined floor/ceiling profiles. Despite facing Rea, **Trea Turner** remains our primary engine for Stolen Bases; his aggressive leadoff spot provides a 10% boost to his efficiency score, even accounting for a slight penalty due to Rea\u2019s status as an elite hold pitcher. Meanwhile, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (61.34) emerges as a fascinating start; despite a tough matchup against Nola, his massive 14% platoon edge and the necessity of prioritizing speed in our Roto format push him firmly into \"Strong\" territory.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision involved **Dillon Dingler** (36.01), who fell just shy of our 40.0 efficiency floor. While he benefits from the same park factors as **Colt Keith**, the combination of a negative platoon split against Gray and a bottom-tier expected efficiency forced his benching to protect our limited game caps. Elsewhere, we continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich**, who remains on the IL, and minor leaguers like **Zac Veen**, both of whom are unavailable for selection. As for our depth, players such as **Lars Nootbaar**, **Chase Meidroth**, **Gary Sanchez**, **Josh Smith**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, **Carson Benge**, and **Luis Pena** were reviewed, but today\u2019s optimized lineup\u2014anchored by the disciplined plate approach of **Junior Caminero** (57.44) and the defensive/speed versatility of **Victor Scott II** (44.94)\u2014represents the most efficient path to category gains across the 5x5 spectrum. Watch for cold conditions or late weather shifts, as the gap between our starters and bench remains razor-thin.",
